<subSubSection pageId="8" pageNumber="153" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1437,1369,2008]" pageId="8" pageNumber="153">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,322,1477,1503]" pageId="8" pageNumber="153">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Pett &amp; Perger, 2021" authorityName="Pett &amp; Perger" authorityYear="2021" box="[329,569,1477,1503]" class="Arachnida" family="Corinnidae" genus="Myrmecotypus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="8" pageNumber="153" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rubioi" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[329,569,1477,1503]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="153">Myrmecotypus rubioi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[577,667,1477,1503]" pageId="8" pageNumber="153">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[577,667,1477,1503]" pageId="8" pageNumber="153" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
is distinguished from all other congeners by having tibia I spination of 3-2 and coxa II white (the remaining coxae dark) (
<figureCitation box="[749,877,1513,1539]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="10.[151,250,1976,2000]" captionTargetBox="[158,1421,1078,1939]" captionTargetId="figure-429@10.[152,1436,1065,1953]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 7. Myrmecotypus rubioi sp. nov., holotype male habitus (SMNK-ARA 13318): A dorsal; B lateral; C ventral. Please note that most setae are broken off due to storage in ethanol. Scale bar = 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5785391" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5785391/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="153">Figs 7A–C</figureCitation>
). Additionally, the new species has a unique male palpal embolus with two broad embolic discs basal to embolus tip (
<figureCitation box="[928,1058,1549,1576]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="11.[151,250,1262,1286]" captionTargetBox="[162,1427,181,1231]" captionTargetId="figure-17@11.[151,1436,181,1239]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURE 8. Myrmecotypus rubioi sp. nov., male holotype (SMNK-ARA 13318), palp in ventral (A) and retrolateral (B) views. Abbreviations: BR—basal ridge of embolic region, e—embolus, PDe—proximal disc of embolus, RTA—retrolateral tibial apophysis, SaDe—subapical disc of embolus, SD—sperm duct. Scale bar = 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5785393" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5785393/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="153">Figs 8A, B</figureCitation>
), subapical disc well-sclerotized, forming part of the embolus, turning 1.5 times to a tapered, retrolaterally-directed point; and the RTA sharp, thornlike, ventrally projected (
<figureCitation box="[433,521,1621,1647]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="11.[151,250,1262,1286]" captionTargetBox="[162,1427,181,1231]" captionTargetId="figure-17@11.[151,1436,181,1239]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURE 8. Myrmecotypus rubioi sp. nov., male holotype (SMNK-ARA 13318), palp in ventral (A) and retrolateral (B) views. Abbreviations: BR—basal ridge of embolic region, e—embolus, PDe—proximal disc of embolus, RTA—retrolateral tibial apophysis, SaDe—subapical disc of embolus, SD—sperm duct. Scale bar = 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5785393" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5785393/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="153">Fig. 8B</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="8" pageNumber="153" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1437,1369,2008]" pageId="8" pageNumber="153">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1657,1683]" pageId="8" pageNumber="153">Remarks.</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Rubio, G. D. &amp; Arbino, M. O." box="[322,585,1657,1683]" pageId="8" pageNumber="153" pagination="65 - 68" refId="ref7534" refString="Rubio, G. D. &amp; Arbino, M. O. (2009) The first Myrmecotypus O. P. - Cambridge (Araneae: Corinnidae) from Argentina: description of Myrmecotypus iguazu new species. Zootaxa, 2158 (1), 65 - 68. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 2158.1.6" type="journal article" year="2009">Rubio &amp; Arbino (2009)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="Perger, R. &amp; Rubio G. D." box="[639,910,1657,1684]" pageId="8" pageNumber="153" pagination="151 - 164" refId="ref6949" refString="Perger, R. &amp; Rubio G. D. (2020 a) Contributions to the knowledge of Neotropical ant-like spiders: Myrmecotypus tahyinandu sp. n. from Bolivian Chiquitano forest, a new country record for M. niger, and indirect evidence for species-specific mimicry (Araneae: Corinnidae: Castianeirinae). Zootaxa, 4790 (1), 151 - 164. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4790.1.9" type="journal article" year="2020">Perger &amp; Rubio (2020a)</bibRefCitation>
hypothesized that some Neotropical species of 
<taxonomicName authority="Pavesi, 1881" authorityName="Pavesi" authorityYear="1881" box="[151,467,1693,1719]" class="Arachnida" family="Corinnidae" genus="Apochinomma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="8" pageNumber="153" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,313,1693,1719]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="153">Apochinomma</emphasis>
Pavesi, 1881
</taxonomicName>
may belong to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="O. Pickard-Cambridge" authorityYear="1894" box="[650,815,1694,1719]" class="Arachnida" family="Corinnidae" genus="Myrmecotypus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="8" pageNumber="153" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[650,815,1694,1719]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="153">Myrmecotypus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Amongst those species, 
<taxonomicName authority="Mello-Leitao, 1939" authorityName="Mello-Leitao" authorityYear="1939" class="Arachnida" family="Corinnidae" genus="Apochinomma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="8" pageNumber="153" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="formicoides">
<emphasis box="[1107,1272,1693,1720]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="153">A. formicoides</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Mello-Leitao, C. F. de" pageId="8" pageNumber="153" pagination="281 - 294" refId="ref6591" refString="Mello-Leitao, C. F. de (1939) Aracnidos Anex I ao Relat. Excurs. cient. Inst. O. Quiz. Boletim Biologico Sao Paulo, New Series, 4, 281 - 294." type="journal article" year="1939">Mello-Leitão, 1939</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
is the only species with a sub-globose abdomen and light coxa II (remaining coxae dark) (
<bibRefCitation author="Mello-Leitao, C. F. de" box="[1208,1424,1729,1755]" pageId="8" pageNumber="153" pagination="281 - 294" refId="ref6591" refString="Mello-Leitao, C. F. de (1939) Aracnidos Anex I ao Relat. Excurs. cient. Inst. O. Quiz. Boletim Biologico Sao Paulo, New Series, 4, 281 - 294." type="journal article" year="1939">Mello-Leitão 1939</bibRefCitation>
). Unfortunately, the female 
<typeStatus box="[452,550,1765,1791]" pageId="8" pageNumber="153">holotype</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mello-Leitao" authorityYear="1939" box="[593,759,1765,1792]" class="Arachnida" family="Corinnidae" genus="Apochinomma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="8" pageNumber="153" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="formicoides">
<emphasis box="[593,759,1765,1792]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="153">A. formicoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was not available for study, and it is probably lost (
<bibRefCitation author="World Spider Catalog" pageId="8" pageNumber="153" refId="ref7660" refString="World Spider Catalog (2021) World Spider Catalog. Version 19.5. Natural History Museum Bern. Available from http: // wsc. nmbe. ch (accessed 2 April 2021)" type="url" year="2021">World Spider Catalog 2021</bibRefCitation>
; A. Kury, pers. comm.). According to the description and illustration that were provided by 
<bibRefCitation author="Mello-Leitao, C. F. de" box="[151,382,1837,1863]" pageId="8" pageNumber="153" pagination="281 - 294" refId="ref6591" refString="Mello-Leitao, C. F. de (1939) Aracnidos Anex I ao Relat. Excurs. cient. Inst. O. Quiz. Boletim Biologico Sao Paulo, New Series, 4, 281 - 294." type="journal article" year="1939">Mello-Leitão (1939)</bibRefCitation>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mello-Leitao" authorityYear="1939" box="[393,556,1837,1864]" class="Arachnida" family="Corinnidae" genus="Apochinomma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="8" pageNumber="153" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="formicoides">
<emphasis box="[393,556,1837,1864]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="153">A. formicoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished from 
<taxonomicName authority="Pett &amp; Perger, 2021" authorityName="Pett &amp; Perger" authorityYear="2021" box="[858,962,1837,1863]" class="Arachnida" family="Corinnidae" genus="Myrmecotypus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="8" pageNumber="153" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rubioi" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[858,962,1837,1863]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="153">M. rubioi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[969,1058,1837,1863]" pageId="8" pageNumber="153">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[969,1058,1837,1863]" pageId="8" pageNumber="153" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
by a carapace index of ~42 (
<quantity box="[1379,1436,1837,1864]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.4986" pageId="8" pageNumber="153" unit="in" value="59.0">59 in</quantity>
the new species), the cephalic area with lateral borders subparallel (narrowing in anterior direction in the new species), and tibia I spination of 3-3 (3- 
<quantity box="[554,599,1909,1935]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.08" pageId="8" pageNumber="153" unit="in" value="2.0">2 in</quantity>
the new species).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="8" pageNumber="153" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1437,1369,2008]" pageId="8" pageNumber="153">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1945,1971]" pageId="8" pageNumber="153">Etymology.</emphasis>
The species epithet is a genitive patronym in honour of Argentinian arachnologist, Dr. Gonzalo D. Rubio (
<collectingCountry box="[234,352,1981,2008]" name="Argentina" pageId="8" pageNumber="153">Argentina</collectingCountry>
), for his substantial contributions to the knowledge on Neotropical ant-like spiders.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
