<subSubSection lastPageId="10" lastPageNumber="155" pageId="9" pageNumber="154" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,1009,2044]" box="[199,345,1009,1035]" pageId="9" pageNumber="154">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,1009,1035]" pageId="9" pageNumber="154">Description.</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,1009,2044]" pageId="9" pageNumber="154">
<emphasis box="[199,369,1046,1071]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="154">Measurements.</emphasis>
Total length 3.63. Carapace: length 1.74, width 1.03, index 59, height 0.67. Cephalic region: width 0.62, index 60. Abdomen: length 1.80 (1.89 incl. pedicel), width 1.10, index 58. Sternum: length 0.81, width 0.60, index 74. Chelicerae: length 0.51, width 0.35. Eyes: AME 0.09, ALE 0.06, PME 0.07, PLE 0.06. Legs: I = 3.04 (0.82, 0.32, 0.81, 0.62, 0.47); II = 3.11 (0.81, 0.30, 0.75, 0.67, 0.58); III = 2.73 (0.78, 0.26, 0.68, 0.63, 0.38); IV = 4.25 (1.20, 0.38, 1.04, 1.05, 0.58).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,1009,2044]" pageId="9" pageNumber="154">
<emphasis box="[199,316,1225,1251]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="154">Carapace:</emphasis>
Broad oval-shaped dorsally (
<figureCitation box="[634,721,1225,1251]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="10.[151,250,1976,2000]" captionTargetBox="[158,1421,1078,1939]" captionTargetId="figure-429@10.[152,1436,1065,1953]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 7. Myrmecotypus rubioi sp. nov., holotype male habitus (SMNK-ARA 13318): A dorsal; B lateral; C ventral. Please note that most setae are broken off due to storage in ethanol. Scale bar = 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5785391" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5785391/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="154">Fig. 7A</figureCitation>
), subtruncate anteriorly. Deep reddish-brown, with longish simple white hairs laterally and frontally, absent medially. No depression, highest point just posterior to fovea, slope towards cephalic region very gentle, slope posterior towards pedicel abrupt (
<figureCitation box="[893,979,1297,1324]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="10.[151,250,1976,2000]" captionTargetBox="[158,1421,1078,1939]" captionTargetId="figure-429@10.[152,1436,1065,1953]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 7. Myrmecotypus rubioi sp. nov., holotype male habitus (SMNK-ARA 13318): A dorsal; B lateral; C ventral. Please note that most setae are broken off due to storage in ethanol. Scale bar = 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5785391" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5785391/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="154">Fig. 7B</figureCitation>
). Sparse short setae near lateral margins.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,1009,2044]" pageId="9" pageNumber="154">
<emphasis box="[199,302,1333,1359]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="154">Sternum:</emphasis>
Concolorous with carapace, roughly shield-shaped, parallel straight lateral margins at region of coxae II (
<figureCitation box="[186,275,1369,1395]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="10.[151,250,1976,2000]" captionTargetBox="[158,1421,1078,1939]" captionTargetId="figure-429@10.[152,1436,1065,1953]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 7. Myrmecotypus rubioi sp. nov., holotype male habitus (SMNK-ARA 13318): A dorsal; B lateral; C ventral. Please note that most setae are broken off due to storage in ethanol. Scale bar = 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5785391" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5785391/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="154">Fig. 7C</figureCitation>
). Short, fine silver setae present, sparse. Anteriorly truncated. Coxae II white, other coxae dark brown, right coxae III with lighter basal 1/3 and may be aberrant.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,1009,2044]" pageId="9" pageNumber="154">
<emphasis box="[199,261,1442,1467]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="154">Eyes:</emphasis>
AER weakly recurved, AME about 2x larger than ALEs, ALE and PME clearly the smallest eyes. PER almost straight, weakly recurved in dorsal view, very weakly recurved in frontal view. AME clearly larger than other eyes. Long ocular setae.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,1009,2044]" pageId="9" pageNumber="154">
<emphasis box="[199,262,1550,1575]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="154">Legs:</emphasis>
Legs I and II light yellow, with femora I and II with basal 1/3 dark, legs III and IV dark brown to reddish, with basal ½ of patellae III and IV light yellow. Femora with pair of strong dorsal spines, basal one about twice as long and thicker (spines on femora III and IV about ½ femur length). Basal portion of femora with mix of very short fine simple and feathery silver setae, more abundant on F III and IV. Tibia I with 3-2 spines, metatarsus I with 2-2 tibial spines.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,1009,2044]" pageId="9" pageNumber="154">
<emphasis box="[199,331,1729,1755]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="154">Chelicerae:</emphasis>
Lighter than carapace, orange. Two small teeth on retromargin, distal one slightly larger, two teeth on promargin, distal one about twice the size of basal tooth, both promarginal teeth larger than retromarginal teeth. One tiny denticle more distal than distal tooth on promargin.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,1009,2044]" lastBlockId="10.[151,1437,151,1041]" lastPageId="10" lastPageNumber="155" pageId="9" pageNumber="154">
<emphasis box="[199,314,1837,1863]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="154">Abdomen:</emphasis>
Pyriform, broadest at posterior half, without constriction (
<figureCitation box="[970,1098,1837,1863]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="10.[151,250,1976,2000]" captionTargetBox="[158,1421,1078,1939]" captionTargetId="figure-429@10.[152,1436,1065,1953]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 7. Myrmecotypus rubioi sp. nov., holotype male habitus (SMNK-ARA 13318): A dorsal; B lateral; C ventral. Please note that most setae are broken off due to storage in ethanol. Scale bar = 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5785391" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5785391/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="154">Figs 7A–C</figureCitation>
). Deep red, darkest at anterior 1/3. Lateral regions not covered by sclerites, pale orangish-brown. Dorsal sclerite covering 4/5 of dorsum, moderately shiny, with sparse shallow punctures. Short, feathery fine silvery setae throughout, sparser further from anterior portion, long and straight erect simple white setae sparse dorsally, density highest in indistinct band at ¼ abdomen length. Two pairs of thick pedicellate setae, first pair at anterior margin of dorsum, rising at 10’30 position, just posterior to this are a second thicker and spine-like pair, projecting at 1 o’clock position. Venter with sclerite occupying middle ½, barrel-shaped, with wide posterior margins and recurved posterior edge. Small wedge-shaped inframamillary sclerite just anterior to spinnerets. Ventral and inframamillary sclerites light reddish-orange. Wellsclerotized full epigastric sclerite wrapping around pedicel and anterior portion of abdomen. Lateral regions not covered by sclerites, pale orangish-brown.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1437,151,1041]" pageId="10" pageNumber="155">
<emphasis box="[199,261,295,321]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="155">Palp:</emphasis>
Bulb drawn out into long neck that weakly narrows medially before broadening towards apex. Basal ridge of embolic region obvious as retrolateral protrusion, one broad unsclerotized basal embolic disc proximal to sclerotized embolus. Distal sub-apical disc sclerotized and forms embolus, with retrolaterally directed apex, turning 1.5 times. Sperm duct with two median loops and one more distal lateral loop on retrolateral side. Sharp thorn- like ventrally directed RTA. Long prolateral spine on palpal tibia (
<figureCitation box="[842,968,439,465]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="11.[151,250,1262,1286]" captionTargetBox="[162,1427,181,1231]" captionTargetId="figure-17@11.[151,1436,181,1239]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURE 8. Myrmecotypus rubioi sp. nov., male holotype (SMNK-ARA 13318), palp in ventral (A) and retrolateral (B) views. Abbreviations: BR—basal ridge of embolic region, e—embolus, PDe—proximal disc of embolus, RTA—retrolateral tibial apophysis, SaDe—subapical disc of embolus, SD—sperm duct. Scale bar = 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5785393" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5785393/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="155">Figs 8A, B</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1437,151,1041]" pageId="10" pageNumber="155">
<emphasis box="[199,362,475,500]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="155">Leg spination:</emphasis>
I: F = d3 pl1, T = plv3 rlv2, Mt = plv2 rlv2; II: F = d2, P = d1, T = rlv2 plv2, Mt = rlv2 plv2; III: F = d2 pl1, P = d1, T = pl2 rl2 plv2, Mt = plv2 rlv2, 1 distal whorl; IV: F = d2, T = pl2 rl2 plv1, Mt = d1 pl2 rl2 plv2 rlv1, 1 distal whorl.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1437,151,1041]" pageId="10" pageNumber="155">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,704,582,609]" pageId="10" pageNumber="155">Geographical and ecological distribution.</emphasis>
This species is only known from the 
<typeStatus box="[1154,1202,583,609]" pageId="10" pageNumber="155">type</typeStatus>
locality in Espiritu, José Ballivián province, 
<collectingRegion box="[429,624,619,645]" country="Bolivia" name="Beni" pageId="10" pageNumber="155">Beni Department</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[636,722,619,645]" name="Bolivia" pageId="10" pageNumber="155">Bolivia</collectingCountry>
. According to the ecoregion delineation by 
<bibRefCitation author="Olson, D. M. &amp; Dinerstein, E. &amp; Wikramanayake, E. D. &amp; Burgess, N. D. &amp; Powell, G. V. N. &amp; Underwood, E. C. &amp; D'Amico, J. A. &amp; Itoua, I. &amp; Strand, H. E. &amp; Morrison, J. C. &amp; Loucks, C. J. &amp; Allnutt, T. F. &amp; Ricketts, T. H. &amp; Kura, Y. &amp; Lamoreux, J. F. &amp; Wettengel, W. W. &amp; Hedao, P. &amp; Kassem, K. R." box="[1215,1431,619,645]" pageId="10" pageNumber="155" pagination="933 - 938" refId="ref6707" refString="Olson, D. M., Dinerstein, E., Wikramanayake, E. D., Burgess, N. D., Powell, G. V. N., Underwood, E. C., D'Amico, J. A., Itoua, I., Strand, H. E., Morrison, J. C., Loucks, C. J., Allnutt, T. F., Ricketts, T. H., Kura, Y., Lamoreux, J. F., Wettengel, W. W., Hedao, P., Kassem, K. R. (2001) Terrestrial ecoregions of the world: a new map of life on Earth. Bioscience, 51, 933 - 938. https: // doi. org / 10.1641 / 0006 - 3568 (2001) 051 [0933: TEOTWA] 2.0. CO; 2" type="journal article" year="2001">
Olson 
<emphasis box="[1290,1347,619,645]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="155">et al.</emphasis>
(2001)
</bibRefCitation>
, the locality is situated in 
<collectingRegion box="[428,481,655,681]" country="Bolivia" name="Beni" pageId="10" pageNumber="155">Beni</collectingRegion>
savanna (widely recognized as Moxos Plains Flooded Savannas (see 
<bibRefCitation author="Ibisch, P. L. &amp; Merida, G." pageId="10" pageNumber="155" refId="ref6384" refString="Ibisch, P. L. &amp; Merida, G. (2003) Biodiversidad: La riqueza de Bolivia. Estado de conocimiento y conservacion. Ministerio de Desarrollo Sostenible. Editorial Fundacion Amigos de la Naturaleza (FAN), Santa Cruz, 638 pp." type="book" year="2003">Ibisch &amp; Merida 2003</bibRefCitation>
). This savanna is comprised of a mosaic of grasslands, swamplands and forest islands (
<bibRefCitation author="Navarro, G. &amp; Ferreira, W." pageId="10" pageNumber="155" pagination="250000" refId="ref6668" refString="Navarro, G. &amp; Ferreira, W. (2011) Mapa de Sistemas Ecologicos de Bolivia, escala 1: 250000. RUMBOL SRL-The Nature Conservancy (TNC), Bolivia. [Edicion CD ROM]" type="journal article" year="2011">Navarro &amp; Ferreira 2011</bibRefCitation>
). Based on the approximated GPS data of the collection locality (according to the information by the owner of Espiritu Ranch), it was not possible to determine the accurate ecosystem or habitat associations of 
<taxonomicName authority="Pett &amp; Perger, 2021" authorityName="Pett &amp; Perger" authorityYear="2021" box="[1289,1395,763,789]" class="Arachnida" family="Corinnidae" genus="Myrmecotypus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="10" pageNumber="155" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rubioi" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[1289,1395,763,789]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="155">M. rubioi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="155">
<taxonomicNameLabel pageId="10" pageNumber="155" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
Further studies are needed to determine this.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1437,151,1041]" pageId="10" pageNumber="155">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,361,834,860]" pageId="10" pageNumber="155">Ant mimicry.</emphasis>
In the other Bolivian species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="O. Pickard-Cambridge" authorityYear="1894" box="[747,912,835,860]" class="Arachnida" family="Corinnidae" genus="Myrmecotypus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="10" pageNumber="155" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[747,912,835,860]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="155">Myrmecotypus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the colour of body parts and the colour and distribution of setae increases the resemblance to specific ant models of the tribes Camponotini or Dolichoderini (
<bibRefCitation author="Perger, R. &amp; Rubio G. D." box="[159,413,907,933]" pageId="10" pageNumber="155" pagination="151 - 164" refId="ref6949" refString="Perger, R. &amp; Rubio G. D. (2020 a) Contributions to the knowledge of Neotropical ant-like spiders: Myrmecotypus tahyinandu sp. n. from Bolivian Chiquitano forest, a new country record for M. niger, and indirect evidence for species-specific mimicry (Araneae: Corinnidae: Castianeirinae). Zootaxa, 4790 (1), 151 - 164. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4790.1.9" type="journal article" year="2020">Perger &amp; Rubio 2020a</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Perger, R. &amp; Rubio, G. D." box="[423,496,907,933]" pageId="10" pageNumber="155" pagination="1 - 8" refId="ref7095" refString="Perger, R. &amp; Rubio, G. D. (2021 a) A new species of Myrmecotypus Pickard-Cambridge spider (Araneae: Corinnidae: Castianeirinae) from the Bolivian orocline, imitating one of the world's most aggressive ants. Insecta Mundi, 0860, 1 - 8." type="book chapter" year="2021">2021a</bibRefCitation>
). Unfortunately, the live habitus of 
<taxonomicName authority="Pett &amp; Perger, 2021" authorityName="Pett &amp; Perger" authorityYear="2021" box="[887,992,907,933]" class="Arachnida" family="Corinnidae" genus="Myrmecotypus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="10" pageNumber="155" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rubioi" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[887,992,907,933]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="155">M. rubioi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[998,1087,907,933]" pageId="10" pageNumber="155">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[998,1087,907,933]" pageId="10" pageNumber="155" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
and co-occurring ants were not documented and the loss of setae due to the storage in ethanol hampered the assessment of mimetic relationships. However, as in other congeners, the body size, sub-oval carapace and abdomen mostly resemble ants of Camponotini or Dolichoderini. Additional field observations are needed to identify potential ant models.
</paragraph>
